04977nam a22007335i 9780226700502DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019037869  a9780226700502  a(DE-B1597)549524  a(OCoLC)1145579332  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHV8148.C4bB347 2020 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a363.2322231 aBaer, Andrew S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeyond the Usual Beating :bThe Jon Burge Police Torture Scandal and Social Movements for Police Accountability in Chicago /cAndrew S. Baer. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b13 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistorical Studies of Urban America00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPART I -- tPART II -- tEpilogue -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe malign and long-lasting influence of Chicago police commander Jon Burge cannot be overestimated, particularly as fresh examples of local and national criminal-justice abuse continue to surface with dismaying frequency. Burge’s decades-long tenure on the Chicago police force was marked by racist and barbaric interrogation methods, including psychological torture, burnings, and mock executions—techniques that went far “beyond the usual beating.” After being exposed in 1989, he became a symbol of police brutality and the unequal treatment of nonwhite people, and the persistent outcry against him led to reforms such as the abolition of the death penalty in Illinois. But Burge hardly developed or operated in a vacuum, as Andrew S. Baer explores to stark effect here. He identifies the darkness of the Burge era as a product of local social forces, arising from a specific milieu beyond the nationwide racialized reactionary fever of the 1960s and 1970s. Similarly, the popular resistance movements that rallied in his wake actually predated Burge’s exposure but cohered with unexpected power due to the galvanizing focus on his crimes and abuses. For more than thirty years, a shifting coalition including torture survivors, their families, civil rights attorneys, and journalists helped to corroborate allegations of violence, free the wrongfully convicted, have Burge fired and incarcerated, and win passage of a municipal reparations package, among other victories. Beyond the Usual Beating reveals that though the Burge scandal underscores the relationship between personal bigotry and structural racism in the criminal justice system, it also shows how ordinary people held perpetrators accountable in the face of intransigent local power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBurge, Jon. 0aPolice brutalityzIllinoiszChicago. 0aTorturezIllinoiszChicago. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aChicago.  aJon Burge.  aaccountability.  acarceral state.  acriminal justice.  amass incarceration.  apolice.  arace.  asocial movements.  atorture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069309640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226700502423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226700502/original  a978-3-11-069309-6  Univ